<TEXT>
a former cia agent earned at least 843000 for 
supplying weapons during the irancontra affair according to 
prosecution evidence presented friday 
the government is trying to prove that thomas g clines 62 of 
middleburg va failed to report all of his irancontra earnings 
on his tax returns clines also is charged with failing to report 
his overseas financial accounts to the internal revenue service 
clines reported gross earnings of 265000 for the tax year 1985 
and 402513 for 1986 according to a fourcount indictment 
returned here in february 
according to documents presented in court clines received 
423534 for helping procure arms for the contra rebels in 1985 he 
earned 420238 in 1986 according to testimony 
when the trial in us district court resumes monday the 
government will call witnesses expected to testify about additional 
profits clines and the other irancontra figures earned 
during six hours of testimony swiss financier willard i zucker 
identified dozens of financial documents and memos outlining how 
the arms deal profits were split among retired maj gen richard 
secord iranianborn businessman albert hakim and clines 
zucker who works at a genevabased financial services company 
that handled money for the arms deals testified that hakim and 
secord asked the firm to alter some records 
cash would come into the accounts it was never explained to 
us what that cash was used for or where it was from zucker said 
when cash was going out no one explained to us why we were 
making that payment we didnt receive invoices 
we were told by our clients that this was a white house covert 
operation we were not encouraged to ask questions we were 
supposed to keep track of the money we did the best we could he 
said 
zucker testified that hakim asked the company to revise account 
statements but he did not know when the changes were made or what 
they included 
he said financial documents presented at clines trial were not 
among those altered 
the irancontra affair was disclosed to the public in november 
1986 congressional investigators used hakims financial records to 
trace the paper trail of the scheme during profits from arms sales 
to iran were diverted to rebels trying to overthrow the nicaraguan 
government despite a congressional ban on such funding 
secord testified wednesday that he believed some of the ledgers 
recording the irancontra arms transactions were falsified but said 
he had never seen a forged document related to clines profits 
secord and hakim each earned 139 million during 1985 and 1986 
the documents showed 
in addition 141084 in profits was received by scitech a 
company jointly owned by hakim and secord according to the 
documents presented in court 
secord pleaded guilty last year to a felony count of making 
false statements to the irancontra congressional committees he 
was sentenced in january to two years probation 
clines faces up to 16 years in prison and fines of up to 1 
million if convicted 
</TEXT>
