<DOCNO> AP900908-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
if hostilities erupt in the 
middle east the air force will be armed with smart and deadly 
hightech weapons developed as a result of hard lessons learned the 
last time america went to war 
the southeast asia conflict changed armament development 
forever said julie massoni historian for the air force 
development test center at eglin air force base in the florida 
panhandle 
the air force gave low priority to conventional bombs missiles 
and guns before the vietnam war focusing on aircraft development 
and nuclear arms massoni said 
as a result highperformance jets were saddled with outdated 
munitions some dating to world war ii that limited their 
capabilities in vietnam 
in the late 1960s us jets armed with iron bombs flew more 
than 800 sorties against the than hoa bridge losing at least 10 
aircraft and failing to bring down the span 
in 1972 four f4 phantom ii jets took only 15 minutes to 
destroy the bridge with the first smart bombs the laserguided 
paveway i glide bombs were used with similar success against a 
second bridge 
the precision guided munitions that took out the bridges have 
been termed by some as the most revolutionary change in the art of 
warfare since the nuclear bomb massoni said 
eglins development test center established in 1968 has been 
responsible for many of those weapons and has even more formidable 
bombs and missiles in the final stages of development 
in general these weapons tend to work extemely well if no 
countermeasures are taken said steve kosiak a senior analyst 
with the center for defense information a private think tank in 
washington dc 
the problem he said is most have not yet been tried in battle 
against opposing military forces that can use electronic trickery 
to fool radarguided weapons or smoke to mask targets from 
television and laserguided bombs and missiles 
one exception has been the successful use of laserguided bombs 
in the us raid on libya 
kosiak said the high cost of smart weapons limits their use 
to highvalue targets oldfashioned iron bombs may still be the 
weapon of choice against such targets as factories and massed 
armies he said 
however merely having a hightech weapon even if it doesnt 
work all the time may inhibit an enemy kosiak said opposing 
forces may not turn on antiaircraft radar to avoid having it 
destroyed by a radarseeking missile 
the air force arsenal of smart weapons now includes the 
paveway iii an advanced laserguided bomb and the gbu15 an even 
more accurate televisionguided glide bomb in tests a gbu15 hit 
a billboardtype target measuring 40 feet by 40 feet after being 
dropped five miles away 
eglin has completed development of a rocketpowered version the 
agm130 missile that can be launched from at least 15 miles no 
decision has yet been made on production because of the cost 
according to maj wayne warren of owensboro ky lead engineer for 
the project 
the air force already has a televisionguided infrared missile 
the maverick introduced in 1972 but it is a relative lightweight 
at 426 pounds the agm130 like the gbu15 actually is a kit for 
converting existing 2000pound bombs of which there are thousands 
a tv guidance pod bolted to the nose makes a bomb smart and 
adding the rocket motor to the tail turns it into a missile warren 
said 
another weapon developed during the vietnam war is the shrike 
missile that homes in on enemy radar used to guide antiaircraft 
missiles an advanced version known as the harm or high speed 
antiradiation missile was deployed in 1983 
for airtoair combat us fighters are armed with the 
intermediate range radarguided sparrow and the shortrange 
heatseeking sidewinder missiles the sidewinder was deployed in 
1953 and the sparrow 10 years later but each has undergone 
numerous modifications to improve performance 
the new advanced intermediate range airtoair missile or 
amraam will give pilots launch and leave capability because it 
has its own tiny but powerful radar for guidance it also allows 
pilots to fire at more than one target at the same time 
about 175 amraams have been built but a reliability problem has 
delayed fullscale production said brig gen charles franklin 
amraam project director 
improvements in the manufacturing process are curing the problem 
and the first operational versions are expected to be delivered 
later this year he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

