<TEXT>
the paratrooper recalls 
stepping off the plane a month ago among the first american 
soldiers to reach saudi arabia 
instant sweat it had me wishing we were back in panama the 
24yearold north carolinian said asking that his name not be used 
but we were pumped ready for instant war our feeling then 
was that war was inevitable he said interviewed at the camp 
first named allamerican city and then changed to champion city 
because of saudi objections 
now uncertainty has replaced inevitability with no enemy to 
fight the desert heat and deepening boredom are the most common 
foes 
wed like to know how long were going to stay said marine 
maj drew bennett of new orleans we dont know anything 
morale remains generally high among us troops but keeping it 
high as operation desert shield drags on could be a daunting 
challenge exacerbated by saudi customs that prohibit alcohol and 
discourage women from venturing into saudi communities 
they need to tell me when im going home air force staff 
sgt kenneth williams said ive got a wife and two kids 
among the troops whether air force personnel sleeping in 
airconditioned tents army infantry in trailers or marines under 
the desert sky come the usual complaints the food the heat the 
slow mail service and the shortage of recreational facilities 
theres not a whole lot you can do and theres no time to do 
it in anyway air force sgt chris jessen said during a break 
from working on an f15 fighter jet 
after weeks of grumbling a mail system is taking shape but 
that means some soldiers without letters have to watch others savor 
the words from loved ones 
military chaplains are trying to collect and evenly distrubute 
mail addressed to any soldier any sailor or any airman 
air force officials believed they scored a moraleboosting coup 
when they won time for the troops even women at an 80 million 
saudi military recreational facility that includes a swimming pool 
bowling alley weight room and other equipment 
some women are upset because they have to enter through the back 
door because of saudi sensitivities 
being able to get the ladies in there at all is amazing 
said air force spokesman lt col tom sack 
the military brass is also trying to do more for morale 
gen h norman schwarzkopf made a tour of several camps last 
week and word is circulating that gen colin powell chairman of 
the joint chiefs of staff may visit next week 
the us consulate is trying to help out by arranging a talent 
show 
well have to do some different things to keep up morale 
said col john lemoyne of the 24th mechanized infantry division 
everybody would probably like a cold beer right now but thats 
just not the name of the game over here 
every unit seems to have an entertainer or comedian among the 
ranks 
at the 82nd airborne one of the men entertains the troops by 
reciting lines from old war movies 
a member of a security patrol at a saudi airbase hopped out of 
his vehicle the other day during a sandstorm to etch a message on 
the sandcrusted back window 
beach party 90 the soldier wrote tides out way out 
