baptist convention usa inc 
the 78 millionmember denomination supported president bushs 
decision to send us troops to the middle east but said the 
nation must deal with iraqi leader saddam hussein at an 
international conference table 
i just cant see lives being taken fighting over oil the 
rev tj jemison convention president said after the vote 
the resolution was unanimously approved without discussion by 
about 1500 delegates representing the nations third largest 
protestant denomination 
the baptist convention said bush was correct to send troops to 
the middle east after iraqs invasion of kuwait to enable the 
nation to negotiate from a position of strength 
but there are other moral issues involved the resolution said 
we contend that if the united states wishes for the world to 
move toward a democratic society no matter how horrific the 
position of saddam hussein might appear we must deal with him in a 
manner that he and all powers concerned in the middle east are led 
to the world conference table for a meaningful negotiated 
settlement of the conflict the resolution said 
pursuing a negotiated settlement through diplomacy will save 
lives and billions of dollars best spent to feed the hungry 
clothe the naked heal the sick train the unlearned house the 
homeless and encourage the lonely the resolution added 
the denomination also commended the rev jesse jackson for 
helping secure the release of some hostages 
the rev amos brown chairman of the human rights commission 
said the vote sends a message that us foreign policy needs to be 
consistent and not ignore human rights violations in nations such 
as kuwait saudi arabia and israel 
for instance were not invading south africa to halt 
apartheid he said 
most major religious groups have responded cautiously to the 
us military deployment in the middle east balancing a 
condemnation of the iraqi invasion of kuwait with concerns that the 
united states act out of humanitarian motives rather than to 
protect oil interests 
