<TEXT>
asked why they have not deployed ground troops in 
saudi arabia alongside us forces americas allies have an easy 
answer the saudis havent invited them 
this reply however accurate has failed to prevent increasingly 
strident calls in the united states for its allies to share more of 
the military burden and the risks in the showdown with iraqs 
saddam hussein 
britain says it plans to send more forces to the persian gulf 
possibly including ground troops but other western european 
countries show no signs of similar action citing the lack of a 
formal saudi invitation and various other reasons 
france which has mounted the secondlargest western deployment 
in the gulf in the form of a naval task force says it will not 
help finance the us effort and would probably join ground 
operations only under un auspices 
portugal which has committed one naval support vessel to the 
gulf says its ground and air units wouldnt be effective 
west germany and japan say their constitutions bar them from 
deploying forces in faroff regions although the germans have 
suggested the possibility of a constitutional amendment 
greece italy and australia which have dispatched a total of 
nine warships to the gulf say no one asked them to send ground 
troops and the subject hasnt been considered 
it wasnt necessary said vittorio surdo an italian foreign 
ministry spokesman we think our contribution is important enough 
in other respects 
us officials say the cost of the 100000strong american force 
in the region is about 1 billion a month they are lobbying hard 
for larger financial contributions from allies 
the nations of the european community agreed friday to give 2 
billion in economic aid to turkey jordan and egypt to compensate 
them for trade lost as a result of sanctions against iraq however 
the 12 ec states made no promises to contribute to the cost of 
deploying us troops in the persian gulf 
after the meeting italys foreign minister gianni de michelis 
told reporters we want to contribute to the burdensharing in an 
independent and direct manner and not to the expenses of a separate 
country even though it is an ally 
so far president bushs administration has handled the issue of 
ground troops with restraint it has praised countries for even 
modest naval contributions and made no specific public requests for 
allied infantry units 
but secretary of state james a baker iii during a senate 
hearing wednesday conveyed growing impatience 
wed like to frankly see perhaps a few more ground troops in 
there he said i think that theres a good chance that there 
will be additional ground and air forces 
his comments followed blunt remarks from several senators 
including democrat john f kerry of massachusetts kerry recently 
visited us troops in saudi arabia and told baker he was upset by 
what he found 
i didnt notice any of our other allies and that disturbs 
me kerry said it is one thing to be in the persian gulf on a 
ship somewhat removed from the first line and another to be up 
there in the desert bearing that heat and the immediate risk 
harsher commentary came thursday in an editorial in the new york 
times 
the arguments some europeans and japanese make for vacillating 
are almost as repellent as the vacillation said the editorial 
depicting such allies as sideline soldiers or deadbeats eager 
for us to protect their oil with our blood 
the saudi government has been tightlipped about details of its 
requests for western military aid 
diplomats say these requests are based on the kingdoms specific 
needs and on past military dealings with individual countries for 
example britain and france were involved previously with saudi air 
defense and thus were asked to help in that field 
britain sent aircraft rather than ground troops because this 
is what the saudis asked us for and this is all by invitation a 
british defense ministry spokesman said they operate the same 
type of tornado fighters as we do and therefore have the ground 
force facilities for those 
britain has sent four warships to the persian gulf one squadron 
of tornados to saudi arabia and one to bahrain a jaguar squadron 
to oman and a surfacetoair missile unit to bahrain its total 
force of just over 2000 military personnel is the only significant 
western deployment aside from the united states and france 
several western countries among them denmark and norway say 
they might contribute ground troops to a un peacekeeping force 
but not a uscommanded force 
baker told congress the united states does not want to put the 
military effort under un command 
