<TEXT>
treasury secretary nicholas brady is declaring 
his global fundraising effort a success even though he received no 
specific pledges of new assistance 
bradys delegation returned to washington on friday night 
following an 18500mile journey that saw him hold hurried 
consultations with world leaders in paris london seoul south 
korea and tokyo 
in addition to bradys mission secretary of state james a 
baker iii made a whirlwind tour seeking support from the oilrich 
countries of the middle east 
the united states is trying to raise more than 25 billion to 
defray the costs of the american military buildup in the persian 
gulf and provide emergency assistance to egypt jordan and turkey 
three countries which have been hard hit by the trade embargo 
against iraq 
in each of the capitals brady visited he delivered the same 
message and received virtually the same response 
brady was thanked for coming forward with a plan for 
coordinating assistance and was politely told the country in 
question would have to study the proposal further before making any 
additional commitments of aid 
brady insisted he was not daunted by the lack of specifics 
because he believed the delegation had made a convincing case at 
each stop he said the cost of failing to protect the middle 
eastern oil fields was far higher than the sums being sought in the 
us aid package 
our principal message throughout this trip has been that there 
is a cost which all must share in maintaining a freely flowing 
source of oil brady said 
he said that for japan alone a 10 jump in oil prices represents 
almost 20 billion in higher fuel bills 
for south korea the annual cost in higher fuel bills was 
estimated at 25 billion 
brady said he used those figures in his meetings friday with 
south korean president roh taewoo and japanese prime minister 
toshiki kaifu 
both countries are heavily dependent on the flow of middle 
eastern oil 
oil which was selling for around 18 per barrel before the aug 
2 invasion of kuwait has been trading around 30 a barrel in 
recent days 
flying home from tokyo administration officials were upbeat 
about their chances of ultimate success although one conceded that 
full acceptance of the plan might take a little longer than we 
had hoped 
the administration officials who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said that tokyo was being asked to increase 
substantially its initial pledge of 1 billion 
the officials said the total amount being sought from japan was 
higher than 2 billion with one official saying the request was for 
billions of dollars although he refused to quantify the number 
any further 
one official said he wouldnt be surprised if we got very 
close to the figure being sought even though japanese officials 
during bradys visit had a lot of questions about how the economic 
assistance money would be distributed 
the administration had been expressing unhappiness privately 
about the amount japan has committed given the fact that the 
country has sent no troops to the persian gulf and has a vibrant 
economy which imports 70 percent of its oil from the troubled 
region 
for its part japan has announced it will contribute 1 billion 
to support the military forces in the gulf and has indicated it is 
willing to give humanitarian aid as well 
while kaifu made no specific commitment on additional funds 
us officials said they were satisfied that their proposal would 
get a serious review by his government 
one official conceded that the various reports of dissension 
over the details of the plan did not help that effort but he 
insisted the impact would be temporary 
its where you are a month or two from now that counts said 
the official on bradys plane who declined to be identified 
further he will understand billions of dollars in western 
support for the military and trade embargo 
