<TEXT>
sudan traditionally egypts closest friend 
has broken with its big brother to the north by refusing to 
denounce saddam hussein the junta is paying back favors to iraq 
and trying to avert explosive domestic problems 
but sudans strongman lt gen omar hassan elbashir is 
increasing his own isolation among arabs and within the 
international community by joining the small group of nations 
sympathizing with the iraqi president 
western experts say the policy is calculated to increase 
elbashirs popularity at home he wants to draw attention from 
sudans tottering economy by focusing on domestic sentiment against 
the usled international military presence in the persian gulf 
they said 
aside from sudan the only arab league members supporting or 
willing to put up with saddams aug 2 invasion of neighboring 
kuwait are jordan yemen tunisia algeria mauritania libya and 
the palestine liberation organization 
elbashir refused on aug 10 to join egypt and 11 other arab 
league members in condemning the invasion since then he has made 
trips and speeches denouncing the western military buildup in saudi 
arabia and calling for an arab solution to the occupation of kuwait 
on thursday elbashir told scholars and politicians in sudans 
capital khartoum that the buildup was meant to change the 
geopolitical situation in the area 
its already changed in sudan said a western diplomat in 
khartoum who follows that countrys military affairs closely in 
recent years he said by telephone iraq has become one of the 
sudan governments main sources of weapons to fight a 7yearold 
insurgency in the south 
sudan in northeastern africa is the continents largest 
country the size of the united states east of the mississippi 
river as elbashir drew the country away from its traditionally 
close ties with egypt and the united states after his coup on june 
30 1989 saddam filled the vacuum 
the diplomatic source said saddam last year sent elbashir 
sovietmade t54 and t55 tanks and artillery rockets this year a 
loan of iraqi transport planes ammunition and other military 
hardware prevented the sudanese rebels from capturing the southern 
capital juba the source said 
but he and other experts denied recurrent reports that iraq has 
based soldiers warplanes and scud surfacetosurface missiles in 
sudan since the gulf crisis began sudans government also has 
denied the reports 
other specialists on sudan agreed that keeping a newfound 
friend happy might have something to do with elbashirs position 
but they said more important is his desire to exploit the gulf 
crisis to gain popularity 
although iraq did them a favor the regimes primary concern 
is the domestic situation said peter woodward a lecturer at the 
university of redding in england they believe the antiwestern 
antiamerican sentiment can bring them local popularity 
so far elbashirs extreme martiallaw rule has gained him 
little popularity except from the small but wellorganized moslem 
fundamentalist national islamic front his harsh treatment of 
dissidents and summary execution of 28 officers after an alleged 
coup attempt last spring brought international outrage and 
intensified his isolation 
since the gulf crisis began thousands of sudanese have 
demonstrated in support of saddam and the sudanese strongman has 
visited baghdad several times trying to mediate a diplomatic 
solution 
