<TEXT>
finns are taking a more active role in 
international politics now that they dont have to worry so much 
about upsetting the superpower next door 
this democratic freemarket society has always been cautious 
about swimming in the turbulent waters of international politics 
for fear it would be caught in the cold war battle but with the 
recent changes in the soviet union and with the soviets and the 
west getting along better the finns are getting their feet wet 
we are now driven to take stands on international issues it 
has been less so previously in the circumstances of the eastwest 
conflict said jaakko blomberg head of the political department 
of finlands foreign ministry 
president mauno koivisto whose nation plays host to the 
ussoviet summit this weekend gave a taste of things to come in 
an unusually strong criticism of iraq on national television 
manni manninen special counsel to the president said that we 
have chosen our policy to not get involved in issues over which the 
superpowers disagree themselves 
government officials activists and academics now say there is 
no longer the same basis for being quiet for decades successive 
social democraticdominated governments have repeated the canon 
that neutrality coupled with a security and cooperation agreement 
with the soviet union was in finlands best interest 
the policy was seldom debated in this country which shares an 
800mile border with the soviet union 
many finns on the street still believe that keeping a low 
international profile is the best policy for their country which 
fought from 1939 to 44 in order to remain independent 
but the changes in the soviet union and eastern europe have 
opened up whole new areas for discussion one of them is the 
possibility of finland joining the european community 
such a debate would not have taken place before lets be 
frank blomberg said 
for the first time in a long time a real substantial foreign 
policy debate is evolving said max jakobson finlands 
ambassador to the united nations from 196572 jakobson was the 
scandinavian governments candidate for un secretarygeneral in 
1971 but there was speculation abroad that the soviets blocked his 
appointment because of his rightwing leanings 
in earlier periods there was a sense of living under a certain 
threat and there was a strong consensus in finland that it was 
important to support the policy of neutrality said jakobson who 
is not a member of any party 
presidential counselor manninen said the finnish doctrine has 
been and still is that finland strives to keep herself outside 
superpower conflicts not to involve herself with issues in which 
the superpowers disagree between themselves 
now that the confrontation between the soviet union and the 
united states has more or less ended and is moving toward 
cooperation as manifested in the present gulf crisis this 
doctrine cannot any more be applied because the superpowers agree 
rather than disagree he said 
that doesnt automatically mean we are going to start chatting 
about everything shooting from the hip at everything that moves 
manninen said 
blomberg said of the persian gulf crisis you could imagine 
what the consequences would be if the soviet union and the united 
states had not seen it the same way 
we would in that situation seek a role that we traditionally 
serve that of peacekeepers he said thats what we do 
finland has contributed to every united nations peacekeeping 
operation and currently has more troops on un duty than any other 
country 
while the finns now have more options in reacting to 
international events they know that circumstances change 
our policy has always been and will always be that we are 
cautious said manninen we cannot change our geography so we 
will always be neighbors with the soviet union and they will 
always be a great power 
neutrality is like an umbrella you carry with you in case it 
rains said jakobson you cannot throw it away when the sun 
shines 
</TEXT>
