<TEXT>
despite persistent problems us 
officers say mail is reaching most us troops in saudi arabia 
within eight days 
the officers say thats a considerable improvement over the 
average eight to 10 days of the last few weeks but they 
acknowledge smaller units still dont get mail regularly 
outgoing mail has been impeded by small problems such as stamps 
sticking together in the desert heat the officers said the us 
postal service said friday it was sending selfadhesive stamps that 
dont curl and stick together but overall the system is working 
smoothly officers said 
the military on friday lifted a 12ounce limit on packages sent 
to troops in saudi arabia saying there was now a sufficient postal 
system and airlift capability in place to handle a larger volume of 
mail 
air force maj michael whitaker commander of the main central 
command postal operation in saudi arabia said the military postal 
service agency would notify all post offices in the united states 
of the change 
over the past five weeks since the us began sending troops to 
saudi arabia many soldiers have complained of poor mail service 
marines in the most forward positions appear to have more problems 
than the army or air force 
theres always going to be some glitches no matter how good 
the system is said capt bradley j seibel 30 of edwardsburg 
mich 
his 129th postal company is handling six tons of incoming mail 
daily and the load is steadily increasing 
he said however that incoming mail is processed in 12 to 24 
hours 
on friday 10 clerks sorted mail at the base post office 
mailbags were stacked up but there was nothing to suggest a huge 
backlog 
for american civilians living in saudi arabia and other persian 
gulf arab states mail to and from the united states usually takes 
at least a week more commonly 10 days or more 
seibel said the typical military unit arriving in the kingdom 
doesnt get a whole lot of mail until theyve been here a couple 
of weeks 
he said the army is expanding mail deliveries and will soon 
augment his unit with a reserve company of clerks from athens ga 
marines and air force personnel distribute their own mail after 
picking it up at an airbase 
postal officers said the saudis were helping with mail 
processing and were considering a us request that they work on 
what would normally be their days off including friday the moslem 
sabbath 
all packages are opened by saudi customs officers who look for 
contraband including alcohol tobacco pornography and religious 
items such as crucifixes and the new testament 
under saudi law pornography includes any magazine with pictures 
of scantily clad women including mail order catalogues 
siebel said he knew of only one case of a soldier facing 
discipline for smuggling liquor after his wife sent a package 
containing two bottles of whiskey and one of vodka 
