<TEXT>
the ban on women serving as nurses 
will be lifted monday which would have been unthinkable in this 
strict moslem kingdom before saddam husseins army invaded 
neighboring kuwait a month ago 
the announcement last week was an indication of the social and 
political change that began after king fahd drastically altered 
saudi policy and invited hundreds of thousands of foreign soldiers 
mostly americans to defend his throne 
saudi diplomatic and other sources said the crisis will 
accelerate a discreet move toward liberalization that has been 
creeping through the kingdom for a decade 
some of the changes wrought by the us intervention may not 
last but saudi society appears on the threshold of modernization 
the crisis will have a lot of impact said prince abdallah 
bin faisal head of one of the countrys major industrial 
developments and a nephew of the king it will speed up certain 
ideas that the government has been thinking about for years 
expected changes include a more professional broadly based 
military more freedom for women greater press freedom more 
public say in local matters and a foreign policy of cementing 
alliances 
fear of a backlash from the conservative islamic faithful will 
temper the pace 
theres a feeling that society is still raw said omar s 
bagour an economics professor at king abdul aziz university new 
ideas should be delivered in specific doses so as not to offend the 
religious people 
