<TEXT>
a petition drive has put a proposed 
constitutional amendment on oregons nov 6 ballot that supporters 
and foes alike call the most farreaching school choice measure in 
the nation 
backers of the educational choice initiative or measure 11 say 
it would greatly broaden educational opportunity by giving parents 
the means to send their children to schools of their choice 
public or private 
opponents say it would severely weaken the public school system 
and violate constitutionally required separation of church and 
state 
the proposal would allow parents to send their children across 
district lines to any public school state school aid would follow 
the students 
more controversially it also would grant state income tax 
credits of up to 2500 a year for pupils at private schools 
including churchsupported schools and for children taught at home 
a poll of 600 registered voters conducted in late august for the 
oregonian newspaper of portland found 48 percent in favor of the 
proposal 47 percent opposed and 5 percent undecided the margin of 
error was plus or minus 4 percentage points 
minnesota is the only state with statewide open enrollment for 
public schools it also is the only one that gives tax breaks to 
parents of students who attend private schools but the breaks 
arent so generous as in the oregon measure 
minnesota permits taxpayers to deduct from taxable income up to 
1000 in private school expenses the oregon measure would allow 
tax credits a direct subtraction from taxes owed of up to 
2500 a year 
the office of legislative counsel said measure 11 is similar in 
most respects to the minnesota law which was upheld by the us 
supreme court in 1984 
if the oregon measure is passed it will take effect in the 
199192 school year 
the proposal is certainly the most extensive one of its 
kind said sister catherine mcnamee president of the national 
catholic education association in washington the association 
which represents 200000 roman catholic educators strongly backs 
the proposal 
the idea for measure 11 however largely came from libertarian 
party adherents 
what were most concerned about is quality education for our 
children said steve buckstein a portland stockbroker where 
its performed is not as important as getting a good education 
buckstein an unsuccessful libertarian candidate for state 
treasurer in 1988 is a spokesman for oregonians for educational 
choice which put the measure on the ballot with 127000 petition 
signatures 
opponents say one of their major arguments against passage will 
be that the measure would result in using taxes to aid religion 
i have a basic disagreement with public funds for private 
schools said norma paulus the state school superintendentelect 
their arguments for allowing choice inside the public school 
system are very valid she said but if you lay the initiative 
on top of the existing funding mechanism it will hasten the 
disintegration of the public school system 
the oregon education association the states largest teachers 
union opposes the whole idea 
we believe every school should be excellent said the 
unions president karen famous competition implies winners and 
losers and none of our young children can be classified as 
losers 
the union also would focus its attack on the churchstate issue 
she said buckstein and other supporters say the churchstate 
argument is invalid 
the state will never write a check to a religious school under 
our measure buckstein said and there is no entanglement 
between the state and religion 
supporters compare the tax credits to federal collegeaid 
benefits that can be used at public or private schools 
a recurrent argument of the proposals supporters is that it 
would give low and middleincome parents who now have no options 
the opportunity to choose their childrens schooling 
only the wealthy now have a choice in oregon buckstein 
said right now geography is destiny where you can afford to 
live determines where your child can go to school 
a study of the minnesota system which until this year applied 
only to districts with more than 1000 students found less than 
half of 1 percent of students transferred under open enrollment 
last school year convenience was cited twice as often as academic 
opportunity by those who volunteered reasons on their applications 
