<TEXT>
the superpower summit in helsinki comes at a 
critical juncture in ussoviet nuclear arms control negotiations 
described by some analysts as stalled and possibly in danger of 
falling apart 
sundays session between president bush and soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev is not expected to provide more than a 
symbolic push for arms control the more immediate persian gulf 
crisis is at the top of the summit agenda 
the result may be a delay in the target date for completing a 
longrange nuclear weapons treaty at their washington summit in 
june bush and gorbachev pledged to finish the strategic arms 
reduction talks treaty already eight years in the making by the 
end of the year 
doubt also is growing that the superpowers will complete a 
separate treaty reducing conventional or nonnuclear arms in 
europe in time for a planned 35nation summit in paris in november 
bush has said he will not attend the summit unless a conventional 
forces in europe or cfe treaty is finished beforehand 
the europeans are particularly anxious to see a cfe treaty 
because it is closely linked to german reunification 
marlin fitzwater the white house press secretary said tuesday 
that bush and gorbachev will discuss cfe issues in helsinki but 
will not negotiate on the complex details 
they will be attempting to add the impetus that would ensure 
that agreement is ready to sign and that the summit can be held 
as planned in november he said 
the persian gulf crisis triggered by iraqs invasion and 
occupation of kuwait is more than a distraction for the arms 
control bureaucracies in moscow and washington it also has raised 
a new soviet security concern the sudden emergence of a huge us 
military force in the gulf area 
soviet gen vladimir lobov the military chief of the warsaw 
pact alliance was quoted by the soviet news agency tass as saying 
the american buildup in the gulf drastically changes the 
strategic balance in the region 
gorbachev is likely to seek reassurance from bush in helsinki 
that the us buildup will be reversed once the iraq crisis ends 
said steve lillyweber a defense specialist at the institute for 
defense and disarmament studies in brookline mass 
fitzwater insisted that start negotiations are on track but 
when asked whether bush still expects to sign a completed treaty 
this year he said only well were hopeful 
the start treaty would reduce each sides arsenal of longrange 
nuclear missiles by about 30 percent it would be the firstever 
negotiated cut in this category of arms 
i think it eventually will be finished but the timetable will 
slip maybe into next year said stan norris an arms control 
expert at the natural resources defense council a private research 
organization 
others say the treaty negotiations could unravel completely if 
bush and gorbachev allow the relatively few remaining disagreements 
to fester much longer 
spurgeon m keeny jr president of the private arms control 
association and an advocate of a start treaty said the rapid pace 
of developments in the middle east plus fear of other postcold 
war upheavals could kill support for the treaty 
a treaty is a little bit like a shark it has to keep moving 
forward or it dies he said 
three main issues are holding up completion of a start deal one 
is how far the soviets should be allowed to go in modernizing their 
ss18 intercontinental ballistic missiles which form the backbone 
of the soviet nuclear arsenal 
the other unresolved matters are limits on the soviet backfire 
bomber and soviet efforts to set limits on us transfers of 
strategic nuclear systems to third countries 
