said as the talks picked up after a fiveweek summer break 
the two sides meeting in the main bar and restaurant of the 
andrews officers club swapped offers friday for the first time 
since the talks began in may officials speaking on condition they 
not be identified described them 
republicans submitted a 525 billion plan for next year which 
starts oct 1 it contains 204 billion in new taxes 56 billion 
in new federal fees and 4 billion in defense cuts 
gop taxes included levies on alcohol a limit on state and local 
income tax deductions and a cut in the capital gains tax rate 
bush says the lower rate would raise money by encouraging people to 
sell real estate and other property 
the democratic plan called for 50 billion in savings next year 
and 500 billion over five years 
it relies on 269 billion in taxes and fees and 149 billion 
in defense reductions 
its taxes include levies on energy and gasoline details were 
not available 
unless deficit cuts are enacted by oct 1 the grammrudman law 
will slice 100 billion from federal spending next year an amount 
officials consider intolerably harsh 
the bargainers hope to reach a compromise by monday to give 
congress time to write the measure into law 
