<TEXT>
pope john paul ii on saturday called for 
a narrowing of the gap between africas urban elite and rural poor 
and urged peasants in this infertile nation to redouble efforts to 
improve the quality of their lives 
later the military government announced a general amnesty to 
mark john pauls visit and said it will cover all prisoners except 
those sentenced for political crimes and corruption against the 
state 
the announcement broadcast on state radio said prisoners facing 
the death penalty will have their sentences commuted to life 
imprisonment life sentences will be reduced to 20 years and 
sentences of 10 to 20 years will be halved 
prisoners jailed for 10 years or less and all women and 
prisoners under the age of 18 will be freed the announcement said 
it was not immediately known how many prisoners will be affected 
in his speech john paul said rwandan peasants who comprise 
more than 80 percent of the population of 7 million have the right 
to demand the same health social and administrative facilities 
including credit banking as their urban counterparts 
it is necessary to avoid widening the inequalities between the 
town and the countryside he said 
the message in french was broadcast on state radio as john 
pauls motorcade traveled to the small agricultural center of 
kabgayi 40 miles southwest of the capital kigali thousands of 
peasants gathered in shaded banana groves near villages along the 
route to see him many held small radios to their ears 
john paul told listeners he believed the international community 
was dutybound to contribute to the development of the peasant 
world 
development projects must not deviate from their objectives or 
lose sight that they are for the peasants john paul said 
he said industrialized nations should pay a just price for 
primary produce from poor nations as well as provide humanitarian 
aid when conditions are worsened by famine drought or manmade 
calamity 
this year scores of people have died in a drought that hit 
remote southern rwanda 
on sunday john paul leaves kigali for the ivory coast the last 
stop on a 10day fournation african tour that has also taken him 
to burundi and tanzania 
a senior vatican official traveling with the pope welcomed the 
announcement of the amnesty 
