<TEXT>
the us education department is withholding 28 
million from seattle schools while it reviews the school boards 
decision to relax racialbalance guidelines district officials say 
schools superintendent william kendrick told board members 
friday that the government wants to review the new guidelines 
before deciding whether to release federal funds for magnet 
programs designed to encourage desegregation 
there is a strong possibility that no money will be available 
to us for magnet programs this school year kendrick said in a 
memo 
the new guidelines approved wednesday on a 43 board vote seek 
to reduce mandatory busing by allowing more minority and white 
students to attend the schools of their choice 
the plan allows 75 percent of a schools population to come from 
a single group including whites it also allows 100 percent 
minority student population 75 percent asian and 25 percent 
black for example 
previous guidelines called for a maximum of 50 percent from any 
one minority group 70 percent total minorities or 65 percent white 
supporters said the new guidelines would help curb white flight 
from the district 
critics contended the move was a step back that could lead to 
allminority schools they also said the new guidelines could 
jeopardize federal magnet funds state construction funds and open 
the district to lawsuits 
under federal guidelines a school is considered segregated if 
minority enrollment is more than 50 percent though schools can 
receive money if improvements are made without meeting that 
standard 
board member ken eastlack who proposed the new guidelines said 
he would propose amending the plan to exempt schools that receive 
federal magnet funds 
he said wednesday he was willing to risk the federal magnet 
funds to keep district enrollment up the district loses 3400 in 
state funds when a student leaves the district 
magnet programs will be in place when students return to school 
monday but officials are unsure how long the programs can continue 
without federal funds five high schools and 14 elementary schools 
had magnet programs last year 
the education department has requested information on how the 
new racialbalance guidelines will affect integration said patty 
mcdonald district communityrelations director 
the agency will then determine whether the district still 
qualifies for magnet funds mcdonald said she was unsure whether 
the district would eliminate the magnet programs or try to cut 
other parts of the district budget 
the new guidelines will not take effect immediately but would 
give 3000 students on a waiting list a better chance of attending 
the school of their choice 
last year the district was allotted 32 million in federal 
magnet funds 
even before wednesdays vote the education department withheld 
417000 from last years magnet package for two high schools the 
agency considered segregated giving the district until sept 15 to 
find a way to desegregate them 
seattle schools receive a total of 128 million in federal 
funds this year for other programs including hot lunches special 
education and supplementary programs for academically and 
economically disadvantaged children 
