the shortage initially was reported only in the moscow region 
where the military newspaper red star reported that hundreds of 
soldiers were ordered to temporary duty as bakery workers and 
delivery men 
on saturday pravda said long lines for bread also had appeared 
in leningrad and tula about 125 miles south of moscow the 
workers newspaper trud also reported a bread shortage in 
archangel a white sea port 620 miles northeast of the capital 
a bakery official in tula blamed reports from moscow which he 
said had touched off a wave of panic buying 
the bread shortage comes at the end of a long summer of other 
shortages that have tried the patience of soviet consumers 
including a lack of cigarettes medicine gasoline and paper 
there have been street protests in moscow leningrad and other 
cities and a riot in the siberian city of chelyabinsk a leader of 
the traditionalist faction with the communist party ivan polozkov 
said tuesday that the lack of goods was causing people to question 
president mikhail s gorbachevs economic reform program 
the bread shortage is occurring in the midst of a record soviet 
grain harvest estimated by the us department of agriculture at 
about 215 million tons 
the problem analysts say is that a shortage of fuel and 
machinery is preventing the crop from being harvested quickly and 
transported efficiently to market 
according to soviet press reports a quarter of the countrys 
combine harvesters are idle for lack of spare parts deliveries of 
other vehicles and supplies are behind schedule as a result grain 
had been harvested from only 28 million acres by midsummer down 
from 40 million acres at the same time last year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

