<TEXT>
the bush administration reiterated in a 
supreme court court brief friday that the 1973 decision legalizing 
abortion should be overturned but it stopped short of asking the 
justices to do so in pending cases involving new york city family 
planning clinics 
the justice department stated its wellknown views on the 
landmark roe vs wade decision in a brief filed to defend reagan 
administration regulations that prohibit governmentfinanced family 
planning clinics from providing abortion counseling 
the regulations promulgated by the department of health and 
human services in 1988 have been challenged by family planning 
clinics planned parenthood and other organizations 
the brief filed by solicitor general kenneth starr said we 
continue to believe that roe was wrongly decided and should be 
overruled 
the supreme courts conclusions in roe that there is a 
fundamental right to an abortion and that the government has no 
compelling interest in protecting prenatal human life throughout 
pregnancy find no support in the text structure or history of the 
constitution starr argued 
but the justice department stopped short of asking the court to 
use the two cases before it as the occassion for undoing roe vs 
wade instead the justice department offered a narrow defense of 
the 1988 regulations 
the executive director of the national abortion rights action 
league seized on the brief as an occasion to emphasize its concern 
about the nomination of david souter to the court which it said 
should be opposed if souter does not recognize a right to abortion 
this is direct evidence that there is reason to fear judge 
souter said kate michelman the administration must feel 
confident they will soon have the votes to overturn roe 
the national right to life committee on the other hand said it 
was glad the administration had presented a firm principled 
defense of unborn babies 
the clinics are financed under a 200 million a year program 
under title 10 of the public health service act the law forbids 
the clinics from performing abortions but earlier regulations had 
allowed counselors to advise women that terminating a pregnancy was 
an option 
the court is considering two cases from new york city in which 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals upheld the 1988 regulations 
on a 21 vote but some other federal appeals courts have ruled the 
regulations were unconstitutional 
the justice department disputed the petitioners claim that the 
regulations violate the constitutional protection of freedom of 
speech the grant recipientss employees as a matter of the 
employment relationship are obligated to comply with the grant 
recipients directions the department said 
thus any limitation on the employees freedom of expression 
arises from their voluntary decision to enter a particular 
employment relationship nor do the regulations infringe on the 
right to abortion that is recognized by roe vs wade said the 
department 
while under roe the government may not prohibit a woman from 
choosing to have a first trimester abortion this court has 
repeatedly held that the government is not obligated to provide the 
means to exercise any such right the department said 
