<TEXT>
after katherine baker finishes telling 
the tale of her escape from the middle east an awkward silence 
spreads across the gymnasium bleachers at central catholic high 
any questions come on no one has any questions katherine 
asks looking out at the teenage audience wilting in the late 
summer heat 
katherine sees the kind of wideopen midwestern faces she her 
brother and sister knew as students in this rural city about an 
hour northwest of indianapolis 
she is trying to reach them with images of kuwaits modern 
downtown its ancient gold souks the arabic peoples warmth 
telling these students about that foreign faraway life is all she 
can do now 
because that life as if a mirage is gone 
like her brother bill baker katherine lost everything on aug 
2 when saddam husseins troops crossed from iraq into kuwait she 
awoke on that day to the sound of artillery she since has slept 
fitfully if at all 
for the bakers this international crisis is a personal crisis 
but more than the financial stability and treasured possessions 
lost they are mourning and fighting for what kuwait was to them 
shes making the middle east real for the kids said steve 
eddy a social studies teacher at central catholic some 
americans feel the hostages deserved to be victims the kids have 
asked what americans were doing there anyway 
katherine 37 was a retail manager happily settled in a house 
near the sea after 3 years in kuwait she finally had made a home 
for her two wrinklefaced pups artwork antiques and other 
souvenirs collected over a decade living abroad 
bill who was on vacation in france when iraq invaded was a 
contractor and consultant in kuwait in the middle east hed found 
a place to start anew after divorcing his wife 11 years ago he was 
financially welloff enjoying a porsche and 42foot sailboat hed 
cultivated an international circle of friends and an understanding 
of arab culture 
that country is a little gem said bill 40 his ruddy and 
animated face momentarily wooden but its gone that life my 
loves my boat my baby mug 
the bakers have lost their touchstones they now live nowhere 
and own next to nothing a pair of sneakers some jeans a few 
photos whatever katherine stuffed into her hastily packed bag 
suddenly these independent world travelers have come home to 
bunk with their middle sister sarah or maybe with their widowed 
mother in springfield ill 
young americans have never known war and studies indicate 
would likely have trouble finding kuwait which is one fifth the 
size of indiana on a map and yet since summers calm was 
shattered they have heard daily reports on americans held hostage 
and soldiers deployed in the middle east 
be aware know the world and that it is very small today 
katherine urges the kids at her alma mater i wouldnt be here if 
it werent for my kuwaiti friends 
the first student tentatively raises a hand then more follow 
with questions they want to know was kuwait a democracy or a 
dictatorship what exactly are american troops over there to 
protect would she live there again 
katherine is grabbing their attention with a real story about 
how accepting people with a different religion looks or culture 
saved her life 
she is talking both about the european friends with whom she 
toughed out the sieges first days and about the natives who helped 
her to safety after 12 days in hiding 
at great risk a kuwaiti family shed never met before and may 
never see again brought katherine and her german boyfriend 
disguised in traditional black religious robes along in their 
caravan across the desert 
iraqi troops twice turned the fourjeep convoy back at the 
citys outskirts before the group navigated a route out under the 
deserts 120degree sun her kuwaiti allies never flinched 
the group stopped only briefly during their fourhour dash 
once to pick up a disoriented and dehydrated arab whose car had 
broken down hours earlier the second time to free a jeep stuck in 
the sand 
i saw a lot of abandoned cars a lot and thats sad 
katherine said i know a lot of my friends their families have 
died 
katherine crouched in the jeeps rear wedged between gas cans 
and her trembling dogs 
two weeks before things were fine i was living a normal 
life katherine said then all of a sudden youre running 
through the desert with a dog hugging you 
when katherine finally reached the saudi border she was not 
elated too many people had been left behind along with the baby 
photos letters and other possessions of a lifetime 
i feel a great debt to those people said katherine running 
a hand through the hair she cropped short after friends reported 
iraqi troops were raping women i owe them my freedom 
bill too feels an allegiance his friends who helped 
katherine escape now are penniless and frozen out of their 
homeland weve got to build back he said when the doors 
open well be ready 
bill plans to organize a group of contractors technicians 
computer specialists and others to go in and rebuild when kuwait is 
freed as he is sure one day it will be katherine plans to work 
with the coming home committee a group based in champaign ill 
that is working to help hostages and their families 
brush it off get on keep busy says sarah 38 a professor 
of radiologic technology at indiana university her indianapolis 
home is a refuge for bill and katherine whose spirits are 
bolstered by seeing uncle bob eating corn on the cob sailing and 
other hallmarks of childhood summers 
but the bakers cant wipe their slates clean and begin fresh in 
