is it an economic crisis yet or still just 
political 
that was the question on business minds as the persian gulf 
standoff dragged through its fifth week 
the financial markets hit hard when iraq invaded kuwait aug 2 
have tried to reach an uneasy peace with the mideast situation but 
oil prices resumed their climb during the past week causing 
periodic retreats in the stock market 
while panic has largely subsided the threat of calamity 
remains a crisis resolved peacefully would have mostly political 
consequences a war might spell economic disaster 
experts likened the markets current conundrum to the strain of 
past war scares a headline in forbes magazines sept 17 edition 
screamed remember the maine in reference to the markets 
performance after saboteurs blew up a us battleship in havana 
harbor in february 1898 
the market lost about 16 percent of its value within a month of 
that incident but then rebounded strongly in a socalled 
sighofrelief rally 
some would argue the markets have already heaved their sigh this 
time about two weeks ago and are getting jittery all over again 
thats the other lesson of history observers pointed out even 
after shaking off political fears the markets may be hit by a 
second wave of worries over the longer term economic impact of a 
crisis 
