<TEXT>
in just a few days opec marks its 30th 
anniversary but with one of its founding members occupying 
another there is little to celebrate 
its a birthday but not a happy birthday said peter bogin 
associate director for oil markets at cambridge energy research 
associates in paris 
they can celebrate their survival thats all they can 
celebrate said pierre terzian editor of the parisbased 
newsletter petrostrategies 
the sept 14 anniversary of the founding of the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries will pass with little fanfare no 
ceremony is planned at its headquarters in vienna some countries 
may issue commemorative stamps hold news conferences or otherwise 
mark the day 
but as it enters its fourth decade opec is in crisis 
a little more than a month ago iraq invaded and occupied its 
tiny neighbor kuwait in a dispute over oil wealth the united 
states launched a massive military buildup in saudi arabia another 
opec member also in the oilrich persian gulf an international 
embargo was slapped on iraqi and kuwaiti crude pulling 4 million 
barrels of oil a day off the market 
with tensions running high opec appears to have given up 
exerting control over its members a majority of nations recently 
agreed to throw out temporarily the cartels output quotas to allow 
as much pumping as possible they intend to make up most of the 
shortfall of banned iraqi and kuwaiti oil 
what we have done is put opec to sleep until the crisis is 
over said sheikh ali khalifa alsabah the finance minister for 
kuwaits governmentinexile and its former oil chief 
terzian argued that by suspending its quota system the cartel 
has abdicated its role of market leadership to western nations 
it is no exaggeration that the price of oil in the coming 
months will be mainly determined by what the americans want he 
said 
in recent years the organization had worked hard to adopt an 
attitude of cooperation not confrontation with western countries 
that are the key consumers of its product demand for opecs oil 
grew supplies were abundant and prices were generally good 
but with iraqi president saddam husseins lightning strike 
against his neighbor years of hard work vanished 
opecs reputation has been badly tarnished said bogin 
the wests impression is that the cartels oil is in the the 
hands of very belligerent unstable countries he said 
the outcome of the crisis will determine the cartels future 
and iraqs power to dominate the group and push for higher pricing 
policies 
if saddams annexation of his neighbor holds iraq will gain 
additional oil reserves and eliminate opecs main dove kuwait 
which had fought for lower prices 
western countries fearful of iraqs muscle might rush to find 
other fuels to replace oil in running their economies 
but saudi arabia and others could refuse to accept the 
annexation of kuwait creating a permanent split in opec iraq and 
libya stayed away from the cartels latest meeting 
if on the other hand iraqs power is weakened saudi arabia 
and others will emerge in a stronger position and likely pursue 
more moderate pricing policies in the future analysts said 
despite the critical situation few are ready to predict the 
cartels imminent demise 
opec member countries are slaves to oil and therefore they 
need opec said terzian 
he was referring to the heavy dependence of the groups members 
on crude exports to get badly needed money for their economies 
some of which have rung up heavy debts with western nations 
its not the end of opec by any means said john lichtblau 
chairman of the petroleum industry research foundation in new york 
opec has been a fairly important organization in influencing 
world oil prices it will continue to play a role in the 1990s 
he said 
with little publicity 30 years ago five key oilproducing 
nations saudi arabia venezuela iran iraq and kuwait banded 
together in baghdad iraq and set up a group to fight for higher 
prices 
qatar indonesia and libya joined soon after the ranks were 
filled out by the united arab emirates algeria nigeria ecuador 
and finally gabon altogether the countries hold about 
threequarters of the worlds oil reserves and pump about onethird 
of its oil 
in its early years the cartel attracted little attention some 
say only ridicule from the major oil companies which controlled 
crude prices then 
it wasnt until the 1970s that consumers took notice 
an arab embargo on crude supplies to the united states for 
helping israel in the 1973 arabisraeli war sent oil and gasoline 
prices skyward 
crude prices again surged approaching 40 a barrel when oil 
production from iran fell after the 1979 revolution the price 
shock sent the world economy into a tailspin 
in the 1970s and 1980s opec kept prices higher than they 
would have been otherwise said lichtblau 
opecs main function he said has been to regulate its members 
production so there is not too much oil on the market for the 
demand of the united states and other consuming nations 
opec is irrelevant while there is a world oil shortage he 
said it is designed to keep members from overproducing and 
driving prices down 
but its regulating mechanism hasnt always worked 
earlier this year crude prices plunged mostly because of 
overproduction by kuwait and the united arab emirates which 
persistently ignored their opec supply quotas and flooded the 
market with crude 
the fall in prices touched off saddams wrath he complained his 
country had lost 14 billion in oil revenues over the past year 
because of low prices and he threatened to use force against 
countries ignoring their opec quotas 
a few weeks later his troops rolled into kuwait 
</TEXT>
