<TEXT>
as the debate keeps raging over whether the 
united states faces a recession or not many wall street investors 
are resigning themselves to a long wait for a clearcut answer 
naturally there is an abundance of opinions among analysts on 
the subject of whether the economy is or is not headed for its 
first certified period of declining business activity since 198182 
but so far hardly anybody on either side of the argument has 
found sufficient evidence in the economic statistics or in the 
unsettled world political situation to proclaim a verdict 
many analysts see no reason to expect that stalemate to be 
broken any time soon given such imponderables as the eventual 
outcome of the crisis in the persian gulf and that uncertainty 
looms as a particular problem for the stock and bond markets 
there are no two ways about it investment decisions will 
continue to be made in an environment of great unease about the 
middle east said robert brusca chief economist at nikko 
securities international in new york 
in theory at least the unsettled stock market would get a big 
boost if the chances seemed to increase that a recession could be 
avoided and prospects for corporate profits could somehow brighten 
conversely undisputed signs that a recession was at hand would 
stand to bolster the market for high quality bonds and thus foster 
hopes for a decline in interest rates 
but events arent giving much encouragement to the bulls in 
either marketplace as witness the labor departments monthly 
report friday on employment 
the figures which showed an increase in the civilian 
unemployment rate from 55 percent in july to 56 percent in 
august painted a picture of continuing weakness in many important 
sectors of the economy 
at the same time however they did not seem to present a bleak 
enough image to stir any immediate response by the federal reserve 
to relax its credit policy 
the stock market is presumed to dislike this kind of neithernor 
environment worse than just about anything else indeed some say 
the outlook for stocks might actually start to improve once the 
existence of a recession were confirmed 
these observers reason that some of the best market rallies 
begin in the depths of recessions as interest rates fall and 
investors begin to anticipate a recovery to come 
in the past week stock prices bounced around erratically in the 
absence of any such inspiring visions the dow jones average of 30 
industrials closed friday at 261955 up 519 from the week before 
the new york stock exchange composite index rose 145 to 17751 
the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market slipped 
83 to 38038 and the american stock exchange market value index 
was up 38 at 32377 
volume on the big board averaged 11574 million shares a day 
against 12788 million the week before 
james stack publisher of an investment advisory service called 
investech says stocks face a volatile environment over the next 
year fraught with both danger and opportunity 
past experience shows he adds that its only after the smoke 
clears and final economic statistics are compiled that it becomes 
apparent we were already in a recession long before it became 
headline material 
not one of the past four recessions was forecast in advance by 
a poll or group of economists 
</TEXT>
