<TEXT>
american businessmen at this years 
leipzig fair see bright times ahead as east germany converts to 
capitalism but soviet traders found far gloomier prospects 
because the berlin wall went down i thought the prospect of 
selling our wooden homes would be better than before and weve had 
quite a lot of success said orrelle trent president of 
blueberry hill cedar homes in california 
but a few buildings away from where the business center usa 
exhibition was housed the mood was tense at the soviet pavilion 
the introduction of the powerful west german mark throughout east 
germany following the economic merger of the countries july 1 has 
made it hard for the soviets to do business at the fair 
there are far fewer exhibitions because we have to pay for 
everything in hard currency explained vladimir krol a 
representative of elektrointorg a staterun electronics trading 
company 
the leipzig fair is an ancient trade meeting that since world 
war ii has been the showcase for products and technology from the 
communist countries of the soviet bloc 
the fair which traces its origins to 1175 developed in the 
middle ages as a main crossroads for metal trading in central 
europe 
its low point was in world war ii when the site was destroyed 
by allied bombing and the fair was closed but after the war the 
fair was revived into a major trading thoroughfare 
the democratic revolution that reversed communism in eastern 
europe and the unification of the two german states this year 
tempted many western businesses to try their hand at the event 
its part of our allaround strategy to move into eastern 
europe we came to leipzig to demonstrate that were serious 
said christian foster a senior representative of bell atlantic 
corp a regional telephone company 
things are different for the soviets whose pavilion seemed 
strikingly out of place amid showy outdoor exhibitions from 
mercedesbenz and shell oil co a huge bust of lenin stands sternly 
outside the massive concrete showroom which is topped with a red 
star 
krol said the biggest interest in his exhibit was for model 
soviet cars and bronze miniatures of pedigreed dogs that his 
company also markets 
plastic lamps oversized televisions and primitive video games 
elicited little enthusiasm among fairgoers 
east german products were very few those exhibited drew giggles 
can you imagine driving that muttered one west german man 
as he looked at a pickup truck version of the trabant the car east 
germans are trading in for west german cars 
the business center usa attracted 19 american companies while 
dozens more were scattered throughout the massive complex on the 
edge of leipzig among the companies represented were the financial 
concern jp morgan amp co inc and consumer and industrial products 
giant general electric co 
thousands of exhibitors were on hand from 55 countries 
attendance figures werent available 
roger schulz representing the duracell battery company an 
american firm with german headquarters in cologne said his company 
has been coming to the fair since the 1960s 
because we were here before it has been easier for us to 
penetrate the east german and sovietbloc markets since all the 
changes last year schulz said since last fall his company has 
opened 800 sales points in east germany and is still expanding he 
said 
bell atlantic also has business in mind it has signed a 
marketing agreement with robotron east germanys largest computer 
manufacturer and wants to set up a joint venture with part of the 
former state monopoly which is being broken up 
we felt working with robotron would give us access to the 
whole east european market rather than starting from scratch 
ourselves foster said 
the company plans to work out a training program with robotron 
employees to help regenerate the economy of east germany he said 
